can Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Walthers","meanings":["German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Walther</i> (see   Walter  )."]},{"name":"McQuate","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uait</b> ‘son of <i>Uat</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Irish form   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waltke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Jurgen, Wilhelmina.","German: from a pet form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with Old High German <i>waltan</i> ‘to rule’ as the first element, as in   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McWaters","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the personal name   Walter  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wahler","meanings":["German:","from the personal name <i>Wol(d)er</i>, Low German form of   Walter  .","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wahl, Wahle, or Wahlen."]},{"name":"McWalter","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b> ‘son of   Walter  ’."]},{"name":"Walters","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Walther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Wolfgang, Otto, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Bernd, Bernhard.","German, Dutch, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Lauter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Erwin, Kurt, Sigismund, Wolf.","German: topographic name and habitational name, from a common stream name meaning ‘clear’, from Middle High German <i>hlutra</i>, or from any of the places called Lauter or Lauta (Saxony). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and some other European countries.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lavtar</b> or its Croatized and rare Slovenian variant <b>Lautar</b>: from a dialect variant of the personal name <i>Valter</i> (see   Walter  )."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Walter was born about 1265, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with William de Wollashall."},"et":{"about 1265–":"umbes 1265–Surnud","1261–1310":"1261–1310","1286–1328":"1286–1328","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1261":"1261","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1328":"1328",",Worcestershire,England.":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1265–":"noin 1265–Kuollut","1261–1310":"1261–1310","1286–1328":"1286–1328","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1261":"1261","about 1265":"noin 1265","1328":"1328",",Worcestershire,England.":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"about 1265–":"environ 1265–Décédée","1261–1310":"1261–1310","1286–1328":"1286–1328","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1261":"1261","about 1265":"environ 1265","1328":"1328",",Worcestershire,England.":"Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Walter est née environ 1265, à Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec William de Wollashall."},"de":{"about 1265–":"um 1265–Verstorben","1261–1310":"1261–1310","1286–1328":"1286–1328","1265–Female":"1265–Verstorben","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1286":"1286","1261":"1261","about 1265":"um 1265","1328":"1328",",Worcestershire,England.":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","lifeSumm